
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lsirq` baraye didane etela'at dar morede interrupt request-ha (IRQ-ha) dar Linux estefade mishavad. IRQ-ha channel-haye hardware hastand ke device-ha az anha baraye khabar dadan be processor vaghti ke niaz be khadamat darand, estefade mikonand.  Ba `lsirq` mitoonid bebini kodam device-ha az kodam IRQ-ha estefade mikonand.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lsirq` --> 📜 Namayesh list kamele IRQ-ha va device-ha.
    🔹 `lsirq <IRQ_number>` --> 👀 Namayesh etela'at mokhtasar baraye yek IRQ khas.
    🔹 `lsirq -v`  --> 💬 Namayesh etela'at bishtar (verbose) dar morede interrupt controller-ha.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lsirq

    🔹 Namayesh list kolli IRQ-ha.

    $ lsirq 12

    🔹 Namayesh etela'at IRQ shomare 12.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lsirq | grep eth0

    🔹 Peida kardane IRQ-i ke network interface 'eth0' az aan estefade mikonad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lsirq` command is used to display information about interrupt requests (IRQs) in Linux. IRQs are hardware channels that devices use to signal the processor when they need attention.  With `lsirq`, you can see which devices are using which IRQs.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lsirq` --> 📜 Display the full list of IRQs and devices.
    🔹 `lsirq <IRQ_number>` --> 👀 Display detailed information for a specific IRQ.
    🔹 `lsirq -v` --> 💬 Display more verbose information about interrupt controllers.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lsirq

    🔹 Show the overall list of IRQs.

    $ lsirq 12

    🔹 Show information for IRQ number 12.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lsirq | grep eth0

    🔹 Find the IRQ used by the network interface 'eth0'.
